\title{Hmdb Database}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{"Access Human Metabolome Database (220K+ metabolites). Search by name/ID/structure, retrieve chemical properties, biomarker data, NMR/MS spectra, pathways, for metabolomics and identification."}

\subtree{
\title{HMDB Database}
\subtree{
\title{Overview}
\p{The Human Metabolome Database (HMDB) is a comprehensive, freely available resource containing detailed information about small molecule metabolites found in the human body.}
}

\subtree{
\title{When to Use This Skill}
\p{This skill should be used when performing metabolomics research, clinical chemistry, biomarker discovery, or metabolite identification tasks.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Database Contents}
\p{HMDB version 5.0 (current as of 2025) contains:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{220,945 metabolite entries} covering both water-soluble and lipid-soluble compounds}
\li{\strong{8,610 protein sequences} for enzymes and transporters involved in metabolism}
\li{\strong{130+ data fields per metabolite} including:}
\li{Chemical properties (structure, formula, molecular weight, InChI, SMILES)}
\li{Clinical data (biomarker associations, diseases, normal/abnormal concentrations)}
\li{Biological information (pathways, reactions, locations)}
\li{Spectroscopic data (NMR, MS, MS-MS spectra)}
\li{External database links (KEGG, PubChem, MetaCyc, ChEBI, PDB, UniProt, GenBank)}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Core Capabilities}
\subtree{
\title{1. Web-Based Metabolite Searches}
\p{Access HMDB through the web interface at https://www.hmdb.ca/ for:}

\p{\strong{Text Searches:}}

\ul{
\li{Search by metabolite name, synonym, or identifier (HMDB ID)}
\li{Example HMDB IDs: HMDB0000001, HMDB0001234}
\li{Search by disease associations or pathway involvement}
\li{Query by biological specimen type (urine, serum, CSF, saliva, feces, sweat)}
}

\p{\strong{Structure-Based Searches:}}

\ul{
\li{Use ChemQuery for structure and substructure searches}
\li{Search by molecular weight or molecular weight range}
\li{Use SMILES or InChI strings to find compounds}
}

\p{\strong{Spectral Searches:}}

\ul{
\li{LC-MS spectral matching}
\li{GC-MS spectral matching}
\li{NMR spectral searches for metabolite identification}
}

\p{\strong{Advanced Searches:}}

\ul{
\li{Combine multiple criteria (name, properties, concentration ranges)}
\li{Filter by biological locations or specimen types}
\li{Search by protein/enzyme associations}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{2. Accessing Metabolite Information}
\p{When retrieving metabolite data, HMDB provides:}

\p{\strong{Chemical Information:}}

\ul{
\li{Systematic name, traditional names, and synonyms}
\li{Chemical formula and molecular weight}
\li{Structure representations (2D/3D, SMILES, InChI, MOL file)}
\li{Chemical taxonomy and classification}
}

\p{\strong{Biological Context:}}

\ul{
\li{Metabolic pathways and reactions}
\li{Associated enzymes and transporters}
\li{Subcellular locations}
\li{Biological roles and functions}
}

\p{\strong{Clinical Relevance:}}

\ul{
\li{Normal concentration ranges in biological fluids}
\li{Biomarker associations with diseases}
\li{Clinical significance}
\li{Toxicity information when applicable}
}

\p{\strong{Analytical Data:}}

\ul{
\li{Experimental and predicted NMR spectra}
\li{MS and MS-MS spectra}
\li{Retention times and chromatographic data}
\li{Reference peaks for identification}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{3. Downloadable Datasets}
\p{HMDB offers bulk data downloads at https://www.hmdb.ca/downloads in multiple formats:}

\p{\strong{Available Formats:}}

\ul{
\li{\strong{XML}: Complete metabolite, protein, and spectra data}
\li{\strong{SDF}: Metabolite structure files for cheminformatics}
\li{\strong{FASTA}: Protein and gene sequences}
\li{\strong{TXT}: Raw spectra peak lists}
\li{\strong{CSV/TSV}: Tabular data exports}
}

\p{\strong{Dataset Categories:}}

\ul{
\li{All metabolites or filtered by specimen type}
\li{Protein/enzyme sequences}
\li{Experimental and predicted spectra (NMR, GC-MS, MS-MS)}
\li{Pathway information}
}

\p{\strong{Best Practices:}}

\ul{
\li{Download XML format for comprehensive data including all fields}
\li{Use SDF format for structure-based analysis and cheminformatics workflows}
\li{Parse CSV/TSV formats for integration with data analysis pipelines}
\li{Check version dates to ensure up-to-date data (current: v5.0, 2023-07-01)}
}

\p{\strong{Usage Requirements:}}

\ul{
\li{Free for academic and non-commercial research}
\li{Commercial use requires explicit permission (contact samackay@ualberta.ca)}
\li{Cite HMDB publication when using data}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{4. Programmatic API Access}
\p{\strong{API Availability:} HMDB does not provide a public REST API. Programmatic access requires contacting the development team:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Academic/Research groups:} Contact eponine@ualberta.ca (Eponine) or samackay@ualberta.ca (Scott)}
\li{\strong{Commercial organizations:} Contact samackay@ualberta.ca (Scott) for customized API access}
}

\p{\strong{Alternative Programmatic Access:}}

\ul{
\li{\strong{R/Bioconductor}: Use the \code{\startverb hmdbQuery\stopverb} package for R-based queries}
\li{Install: \code{\startverb BiocManager::install("hmdbQuery")\stopverb}}
\li{Provides HTTP-based querying functions}
\li{\strong{Downloaded datasets}: Parse XML or CSV files locally for programmatic analysis}
\li{\strong{Web scraping}: Not recommended; contact team for proper API access instead}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{5. Common Research Workflows}
\p{\strong{Metabolite Identification in Untargeted Metabolomics:}}

\ol{
\li{Obtain experimental MS or NMR spectra from samples}
\li{Use HMDB spectral search tools to match against reference spectra}
\li{Verify candidates by checking molecular weight, retention time, and MS-MS fragmentation}
\li{Review biological plausibility (expected in specimen type, known pathways)}
}

\p{\strong{Biomarker Discovery:}}

\ol{
\li{Search HMDB for metabolites associated with disease of interest}
\li{Review concentration ranges in normal vs. disease states}
\li{Identify metabolites with strong differential abundance}
\li{Examine pathway context and biological mechanisms}
\li{Cross-reference with literature via PubMed links}
}

\p{\strong{Pathway Analysis:}}

\ol{
\li{Identify metabolites of interest from experimental data}
\li{Look up HMDB entries for each metabolite}
\li{Extract pathway associations and enzymatic reactions}
\li{Use linked SMPDB (Small Molecule Pathway Database) for pathway diagrams}
\li{Identify pathway enrichment for biological interpretation}
}

\p{\strong{Database Integration:}}

\ol{
\li{Download HMDB data in XML or CSV format}
\li{Parse and extract relevant fields for local database}
\li{Link with external IDs (KEGG, PubChem, ChEBI) for cross-database queries}
\li{Build local tools or pipelines incorporating HMDB reference data}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Related HMDB Resources}
\p{The HMDB ecosystem includes related databases:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{DrugBank}: ~2,832 drug compounds with pharmaceutical information}
\li{\strong{T3DB (Toxin and Toxin Target Database)}: ~3,670 toxic compounds}
\li{\strong{SMPDB (Small Molecule Pathway Database)}: Pathway diagrams and maps}
\li{\strong{FooDB}: ~70,000 food component compounds}
}

\p{These databases share similar structure and identifiers, enabling integrated queries across human metabolome, drug, toxin, and food databases.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Best Practices}
\p{\strong{Data Quality:}}

\ul{
\li{Verify metabolite identifications with multiple evidence types (spectra, structure, properties)}
\li{Check experimental vs. predicted data quality indicators}
\li{Review citations and evidence for biomarker associations}
}

\p{\strong{Version Tracking:}}

\ul{
\li{Note HMDB version used in research (current: v5.0)}
\li{Databases are updated periodically with new entries and corrections}
\li{Re-query for updates when publishing to ensure current information}
}

\p{\strong{Citation:}}

\ul{
\li{Always cite HMDB in publications using the database}
\li{Reference specific HMDB IDs when discussing metabolites}
\li{Acknowledge data sources for downloaded datasets}
}

\p{\strong{Performance:}}

\ul{
\li{For large-scale analysis, download complete datasets rather than repeated web queries}
\li{Use appropriate file formats (XML for comprehensive data, CSV for tabular analysis)}
\li{Consider local caching of frequently accessed metabolite information}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Reference Documentation}
\p{See \code{\startverb references/hmdb_data_fields.md\stopverb} for detailed information about available data fields and their meanings.}
}
}